[[Junior Achievement]]'s '''U.S. Business Hall of Fame''' was established in 1975,<ref name=SpecialEvents>{{cite web|title=Special Events :: U.S. Business Hall of Fame|publisher=Junior Achievement USA|url=http://www.ja.org/hof/|accessdate=2011-12-12}}</ref> as the result of an idea by Willard F. Rockwell, Jr. (former chairman and CEO of [[Rockwell International]]) and [[Alan Hilburg]] (assisting W. F. Rockwell as a representative of [[Junior Achievement]]).  Rockwell and Hilburg approached Pat Lenahan and Charles Whittingham (publisher and associate publisher of ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine) with the idea.  Together they engaged the Board of Editors of ''Fortune'' to independently select the honorees.  The originating idea was to align the principles of Junior Achievement with the lives of the inductees to promote examples of what it considers exemplary business leadership.

{{TOC right}}

==Location==
The [[hall of fame]] is part of an exhibit at the [[Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago)|Museum of Science and Industry]] in Chicago, Illinois, US.<ref name=SpecialEvents/><ref>{{cite web|title=Museum of Science and Industry|publisher=Junior Achievement USA|url=http://www.ja.org/hof/museum.shtml|accessdate=2011-12-12|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208124854/http://www.ja.org/hof/museum.shtml|archivedate=2012-02-08|df=}}</ref>

